text: World Journal of Microbiology and Biotechnology (2021) 37:62  https://doi.org/10.1007/s11274-021-03030-5 Genetically engineered rpsL merodiploidy impacts secondary  metabolism and antibiotic resistance in Streptomyces Oksana Koshla1 · Maria Lopatniuk2 · Oksana Borys1 · Yuya Misaki3 · Volodymyr Kravets1 · Iryna Ostash1 ·  Anastasiia Shemediuk1 · Kozo Ochi3 · Andriy Luzhetskyy2 · Victor Fedorenko1 · Bohdan Ostash1  Received: 8 October 2020 / Accepted: 8 March 2021 / Published online: 17 March 2021  © The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer Nature B.V. 2021

Abstract Certain point mutations within gene for ribosomal protein S12, rpsL, are known to dramatically change physiological traits  of bacteria, most prominently antibiotic resistance and production of various metabolites. The rpsL mutants are usually  searched among spontaneous mutants resistant to aminoglycoside antibiotics, such as streptomycin or paromomycin. The  shortcomings of traditional selection are as follows: random rpsL mutants may carry undesired genome alterations; many  rpsL mutations cannot be isolated because they are either not associated with increased antibiotic resistance or non-viable in  the absence of intact rpsLWT gene. Introduction of mutant rpsL alleles in the rpsLWT background can be used to circumvent  these obstacles. Here we take the latter approach and report the generation and properties of a set of stable rpsL merodip- loids for Streptomyces albus J1074. We identified several rpsL alleles that enhance endogenous and heterologous antibiotic  production by this strain and show that rpsLWTrpsLK88E merodiploid displays increased streptomycin resistance. We further  tested several promising rpsL alleles in two more strains, Streptomyces cyanogenus S136 and Streptomyces ghanaensis  ATCC14672. In S136, plasmid-borne rpsLK88E+P91S and rpsLK88R led to elevated landomycin production; no changes were  detected for ATCC14672 merodiploids. Our data outline the prospects for and limitations to rpsL merodiploids as a tool for  rapid enhancement of secondary metabolism in Streptomyces. Keywords  Antibiotics · Ribosome engineering · RpsL · Streptomyces albus J1074 Streptomycetes constitute a genus within class Actinobacte- ria, famous for their ability to produce an impressive array  of bioactive secondary metabolites (Barka et al. 2016). As  the latter are usually accumulated in minute quantities by the  wild type strains, there is constant need for improvement of  microbiological production of these compounds (Adrio and  Demain 2006). Identification of improved variants among  spontaneous streptomycin-resistant mutants was shown by  1  Department of Genetics and Biotechnology, Ivan

2  Helmholtz Institute for Pharmaceutical Research, Saarland  Campus, Building C2.3, 66123 Saarbrucken, Germany 3  Department of Life Sciences, Hiroshima Institute  Franko National University of Lviv, Hrushevskoho st. 4,  Lviv 79005, Ukraine of Technology, Saeki-ku, Hiroshima 731-5193, Japan us to be a fruitful approach towards strain improvement, not  only for actinobacteria, but also for the other bacterial genera  (Gromyko et al. 2004; Ochi 2007; Tanaka et al. 2009). The  increased or activated antibiotic production most commonly  arises from point substitutions within the gene for ribosomal  protein S12, known as rpsL, although an exact mechanism  by which rpsL mutations influence secondary metabolism is  not well understood (Okamoto-Hosoya et al. 2003b). Over  the last two decades selection for resistance to translation  inhibitors was successfully used for numerous wild type and  industrial strains, forming the basis of empirical ribosome  engineering for biotechnological purposes (Tamehiro et al.  2003; Hosaka et al. 2009). Current advances in genome  engineering permit rational introduction of rspL mutations  into streptomycetes, as it was demonstrated by us and oth- ers (Huang et al. 2015; Lopatniuk et al. 2019). Two types of  rpsL engineering were adopted. One can replace or mutate  the wild type rpsL allele, leading to the strain that carries  only the mutated version of the gene. This is the most com- mon approach that mimics traditional selection schemes, yet

it is not without limitations. First, overwhelming majority  of all possible point rpsL mutations are not associated with  simple phenotypic outcome, such as increased antibiotic  resistance (Agarwal et al. 2011), and so they cannot be fac- ilely selected for in naive streptomycete strains. Second, it  cannot be ruled out that some rpsL mutant alleles are potent  activators of secondary metabolism, but lethal in homozy- gous state (e.g. when the wild type rpsL is absent). Indeed,  our recent work provides circumstantial evidence for such  scenario (Lopatniuk et al. 2019). Therefore, one may take  an alternative approach and express a mutated rpsL allele  from the plasmid, creating a situation where both mutant and  wild type rpsL genes co-exist within one cell (rpsL merodip- loids). The second approach is devoid of aforementioned  limitations and was shown by us in 2003 to activate the pro- duction of antibiotics in S. lividans (Okamoto-Hosoya et al.  2003b). Recently the merodiploid approach was successfully  expanded also to a combination of rpsL and rpoB mutations  (Zhang et al. 2020).

We are interested in a deeper understanding of the mecha- nisms and prospects for ribosome engineering via generation  of rpsL merodiploids. As a principal test case Streptomyces  albus J1074 was chosen in this work, as this strain currently  is one of the most popular platforms for natural product dis- covery (Tan et al. 2017; Kallifidas et al. 2018; Myronovskyi  et al. 2018). We recently described the development of a  system for rational generation of pure rpsL mutants for this  strain (Lopatniuk et al. 2019). Streptomyces albus J1074  therefore represents an excellent opportunity to compare  the properties of rpsL mutants in pure and merodiploid  states, and to better understand the caveats of both methods.  Here we describe the generation and initial characterization  of a set of rpsL merodiploids for S. albus J1074. Several  rpsL alleles were shown for the first time to be efficient in  merodiploid state, as it is evident from studies on S. albus  as well as landomycin producer Streptomyces cyanogenus  S136. Bacterial strains and growth media Microorganisms, used in this work, are listed in Table 1.  Streptomyces albus SAM2, derivative from J1074 (Bilyk and  Luzhetskyy 2014) was used throughout the study. Moeno- mycin producer S. ghanaensis ATCC14672 (Ostash et al.  2007)  and  landomycin  A  producer S.  cyanogenus  S136  (Westrich et al. 1999) were used for expression of selected  rpsL alleles. S. ghanaensis strains were cultivated at 37 °C,  the rest Streptomyces strains—at 30 °C. Escherichia coli  DH5α was used for routine subcloning. E. coli ET12567  (pUZ8002) was used to perform intergeneric conjugation

from E. coli to Streptomyces.  E. coli strains were grown  under standard conditions (Sambrook and Russell 2001).  Staphylococcus aureus 209P, Bacillus cereus ATCC19637  and Candida famata VKM Y-9 (also known as Debaryomy- ces hansenii) were used as antibiotic-sensitive test-cultures  (cultivated at 30 °C). For intergeneric matings, Streptomyces  strains were grown on SFM (Kieser et al. 2000) or ISP3 agar  (Koshla et al. 2017) at 30 °C. If needed, antibiotics were  used for selection in following final concentrations: kana- mycin 50 μg/mL, apramycin 50 μg/mL, hygromycin 100 μg/ mL, ampicillin 100 μg/mL, thiostrepton 50 μg/mL.

All vectors, cosmids and plasmids are listed in Table 1.  The mutant rpsL alleles were amplified with primers rpsL_ XbaIup (AAA TCT AGA GTG GTT CCC CGT TCC CCGTC)  and rpsL_KpnIrp (AAA GGT ACC TTA CTT CTC CTT CTT  GGCGC) from derivatives of bacterial artificial chromo- some  BAC  1F1  (Lopatniuk  et  al.  2019).  The  resulting  amplicons were digested with XbaI and KpnI and cloned  into respective sites of VWB actinophage-based integra- tive vector pTOS (Herrmann et al. 2012) to yield a pS12- series of plasmids, listed in Table 1. The wild type rpsL  gene was cloned in the same way from SAM2 genome. The  vector sequences of pS12 plasmids integrated into SAM2  genome were evicted with the help of site-specific recom- binase Dre, expressed from pUWLDre, as described before  (Herrmann et al. 2012). Additionally, rpsLL90K allele was  subcloned from pS12_L90K into BT1 actinophage-based  vector pMS82 (Gregory et al. 2003) to give pASH_L90K.  The latter was used to generate a derivative of S. cyanoge- nus S136 carrying additional rpsLL90K allele. The identity of  rpsL in all plasmids and strains was verified by sequencing. Analysis of secondary metabolites produced  by Streptomyces strains To reveal endogenous antibacterial and antifungal activi- ties, S. albus strains were grown on SG2, GYM (Koshla  et al. 2017) and R5 (Kieser et al. 2000) agar plates for 120 h.  Conditions of S. albus biotest assays are described before  (Koshla et al. 2017).

For HPLC–MS-based analysis of antibiotic extracts from  S. albus merodiploids, strains were grown in NL19 liquid  medium (Ahmed et al. 2017) for 144 h. Extracts preparation  was done as described in (Lopatniuk et al. 2019). Analyses  were performed on Dionex Ultimate 3000 HPLC coupled  with a Bruker AmaZon mass spectrometer using C18 col- umn (1.7 μm, 100 × 2.1 mm) and a linear 18 min gradient  from 5% of acetonitrile to 95%. A buffer: 0,1% formic acid  in water. B buffer: 0,1% formic acid in acetonitrile. Precultures were incubated for 24 h at 30 °C in 10 mL  of tryptic soy broth (TSB) and then 500 μL were inoculated  into 25 mL of the main SG1 medium. After 120 h of growth,  aranciamycins were extracted with DMSO-methanol (1:1)  solution from biomass and ethyl acetate from supernatant.  Ethyl acetate extracts were dried in vacuo and residues then  dissolved in DMSO-methanol extracts.  OD445 were taken for  combined extracts and productivity was normalized against  respective dried biomass concentration.

Landomycin production by S. cyanogenus strains was  assayed in liquid medium SG; cultivation and extraction  conditions, as well as the quantification are described in  (Yushchuk et al. 2018). Moenomycin production by S. gha- naensis ATCC14672 derivatives was determined in TSB.  For precultures, strains were inoculated in 10 mL of TSB,  cultivated for 96 h at 37 °C. Then 500 μL of preculture were  inoculated into 25 mL of the main TSB medium and culti- vated for 120 h at 37 °C. Mycelium was separated via cen- trifugation and 500 mg of wet biomass were used to extract  moenomycins with 1.5 mL of methanol. Methanol extracts  then were concentrated in vacuo and used for disc diffusion  assay. For the latter, paper disks (Ø5 mm) were saturated  with methanol extracts from 100 mg of biomass and placed  on the plates with 0.7% agar containing approx.  108 CFU of  B. cereus. Plates were incubated for 20 h at 37 °C. Moeno- mycin production correlates with a diameter of B. cereus  growth inhibition zone (Makitrynskyy et al. 2010). The  production  of  aranciamycin,  landomycin  A  and  moenomycins are given as mean values (of at least three  repeats) with standard deviations. To test whether or not the  difference in antibiotic production was significant as com- pared to the respective wild types (controls), two-tailed t-test  was used to calculate p-value. Streptomycin resistance assays

To  determine  resistance  of  S.  albus  SAM2,  K88E  and  K88E_ex to streptomycin, strains were grown in TSB. Serial  dilutions were taken at appropriate timepoints and either  spread (for quantitative analysis) or spotted (for qualitative  assay) onto tryptic soy agar (TSA) plates supplemented  with 100 μg/mL of streptomycin. Plates were incubated for  three days and number of streptomycin resistant CFU was  counted. For total number of CFU estimation, dilutions were  Description pMS82 derivative; rpsLL90K cloned into EcoRV site  (Hygr) plated on TSA without antibiotic. Fraction of streptomycin  resistant CFU was calculated against the total number of  CFU in one mL of culture. Same was performed for spore  suspensions of SAM2 and K88E_ex strains. Spore suspen- sions were prepared as described before (Kieser et al. 2000),  using fully developed lawns of streptomycetes grown on  SFM agar for at least 96 h at 30 °C. Generation of S. albus J1074 rpsL merodiploids

For generation of rpsL merodiploids, we have chosen actin- ophage VWB-based vector pTOS. The vector is integra- tive and could provide inheritance of mutated allele in the  absence of selective pressure. It is possible to evict pTOS  sequence from genome, except for the cloned gene (Her- rmann et al. 2012). This system allows us to subsequently  express additional constructs (e.g. cosmids directing the pro- duction of natural products) in merodiploids, including those  that integrate in actinophage φC31 site. We cloned nine rpsL  alleles, carrying missense mutations leading to substitutions  R86P, K88E, K88R, L90K, P91S, R94G, glycine codon  insertion in position 92 (GI92), and two combinations of  mentioned above changes: K88E+P91S and K88E+GI92  (Lopatniuk et al. 2019). All rpsL alleles were cloned into  pTOS along with their native promoter. Generated pS12- plasmids were individually transferred via conjugation to S.  albus and clones with integrated constructs were selected  for apramycin resistance  (Amr). We evicted vector sequence  from genomes of pS12-carrying strains using Dre recombi- nase expression (see Fig. S1, ESM). As a result, nine mark- erless merodiploid S. albus strains (named L90K_ex etc.)  each carrying one of the mutated rpsL alleles in addition to  the native rpsLWT were used for further studies. Antibiotic activity of S. albus merodiploids Streptomyces albus J1074 is known to harbor a number of  BGCs (Zaburannyi et al. 2014). Expression of one of them  results in antibacterial paulomycin and paulomenol produc- tion, three more encode enzymes for antifungal candicidin,  surugamide and antimycin biosynthesis (Olano et al. 2014;  González et al. 2016). It could not be ruled out that the  other BGCs within J1074 genome are active under certain

Introduc- tion of all nine mutant rpsL alleles led to increased antifun- gal activity while grown on SG2 agar. However, production  of antibacterial compounds was rpsL allele- and medium- specific (Table 2). For further investigation of antifungal compounds accu- mulation by merodiploids, we performed HPLC–MS analy- sis of extracts from S. albus strains, grown in NL19 medium,  a liquid analog of SFM (Ahmed et al. 2017). For candicidin  detection, UV absorption at wavelength 404 nm was used.  Among the merodiploids, the highest increase in candici- dins production was observed for L90K_ex, R94G_ex and  GI92_ex and moderate increase—for P91S_ex, P86P_ex,  K88R_ex and K88E+GI92_ex strains (Figs. 1, S2a, ESM).  This data differs significantly from the production of can- dicidins by pure rpsL mutants under the same conditions,  where GI92, K88E+GI92 and P91S strains were less pro- ductive than the wild type (Lopatniuk et al. 2019). Interest- ingly, 8 out of 9 additional rpsL alleles (except rpsLK88E)  led to higher accumulation of surugamides (in particular,  major compound surugamide A with m/z 912.62 [M +  H]+);  rpsLR94G, rpsLL90K and rpsLK88R were the most effective  in this regard (Fig. S2b, ESM). We noticed no significant  change in antimycins accumulation (Rt: 16–18 min) by stud- ied strains (Fig. S2c, ESM).

Effects of selected rpsL alleles on antibiotic  production by S. cyanogenus S136 and S. ghanaensis  ATCC14672

Positive effects of rpsL alleles on secondary metabolome  of S. albus SAM2 prompted us to study their utility for two  other streptomycetes: antitumor polyketide landomycin A  producer S. cyanogenus S136 and producer of peptidogly- can biosynthesis inhibitor moenomycin A, S. ghanaensis  ATCC14672. We have chosen following alleles: rpsLK88E,  rpsLK88E+P91S, rpsLK88R and rpsLL90K (based on two dif- ferent integrative plasmids, pTOS and pMS82). We also  introduced the second copy of wild type rpsL gene (as a  part of pS12_rpsL plasmid) into S. cyanogenus S136 and  S.  ghanaensis  ATCC14672  strains.  All  aforementioned  mutant rpsL alleles, except rpsLK88E, boosted landomycin  A production by S. cyanogenus, with rpsLK88E+P91S being  the most efficient in this regard (Figs. 3 and S3, ESM). The  tested rpsL alleles showed neither significant stimulatory nor  inhibitory effects on moenomycin production by S. ghanaen- sis ATCC14672 in merodiploid state (Fis. S4, ESM). The S.  ghanaensis ATCC14672 transconjugant carrying rpsLK88R  allele displayed retarded sporulation on ISP3 and SFM (Fig.  S5, ESM).

If  significant,  p-values  are  given  as  ***p ≤ 0.001; **0.001 < p ≤ 0.01; *0.01 < p ≤ 0.05 Resistance to streptomycin in S. albus: levels  and temporal dynamics

It is of practical interest to understand the level and dynam- ics  of  streptomycin  resistance  (Strr)  phenotype  in rpsL  merodiploids as this may explain why different rpsL alleles  vary in their effects in antibiotic production, and could offer  ways to exploit this knowledge. Currently it is assumed that  streptomycin sensitivity conferred by the wild type rpsL  allele is dominant trait, a feature used in several selection  schemes. Nevertheless, the dominance of the wild type rpsL  in Streptomyces was reported for the cases where the former  was on high copy number vectors (Hosted and Baltz 1997).  Here  we  studied  Strr  phenotype  of  three  strains:  SAM2  carrying wild type rpsL allele; K88E strain engineered to  carry rpsLK88E allele (Lopatniuk et al. 2019); and merodip- loid K88E_ex carrying wild type rpsL and rpsLK88E. In first  two strains rpsL alleles are present in a single copy. First,  we revealed that pure K88E mutant is more productive in  terms of biomass in stationary phase of growth (72–96 h;  Fig. 4a), and it showed practically complete survival on  100 μg/mL streptomycin (Fig. 4b). As compared to the pure  K88E mutant, in the population of merodiploid cells much  smaller  fraction  displayed  Strr  phenotype,  yet  their  fre- quency was two orders above the frequency of spontaneous   Strr clones observed for SAM2 strain both in liquid culture  and in spore suspension (Fig. 4c, d). One may imagine that   Strr phenotype of merodiploids would depend on stochas- tic processes of incorporation of mutated S12 protein into  ribosomes; the more ribosomes within a cell would carry   S12K88E, the more likely the cell would survive in presence  of streptomycin. It is known that certain S12 mutant proteins  (including  S12K88E) render ribosomes less prone to dissocia- tion and degradation in stationary phase (Okamoto-Hosoya  et al. 2003a; Hosaka et al. 2004, 2006

It is known that certain S12 mutant proteins  (including  S12K88E) render ribosomes less prone to dissocia- tion and degradation in stationary phase (Okamoto-Hosoya  et al. 2003a; Hosaka et al. 2004, 2006) which might lead  to increase of  Strr cells with a time. Indeed, we observed  significantly more  Strr variants in liquid 72-h merodiploid  cultures as compared to earlier time points (Fig. 4c). These  variants showed no streptomycin resistance upon passage  through non-selective medium (50 colonies checked), imply- ing that they are not spontaneous  Strr mutants. In contrast,  a few  Strr colonies observed for SAM2 strain did retain  Strr  phenotype upon the passage, implying their mutational ori- gin (data not shown).

In  this  work  we  set  out  to  further  our  understanding  of  rpsL merodiploids as a tool to increase antibiotic produc- tion in Streptomyces. For this purpose, we primarily used  S. albus J1074, a widely popular streptomycete platform  for antibiotic production. our previous findings (Okamoto-Hosoya et al. 2003b) that  engineered rpsL merodiploidy is a way to increase antibiotic  productivity. There are three important amendments of this  work as compared to our study reported in 2003. First, we  reveal novel rpsL alleles that are efficient in merodiploid  state, such as rpsLK88R and rpsLK88E+P91S. Second, we show  the value of single copy rpsL alleles, integrated into genome,  as a means to generate merodiploids with increased antibi- otic production. Our strategy offers a number of advantages  over replicative plasmid-based approaches in terms of strain  stability, marker elimination and amenability for next rounds  of genetic engineering, and control over rpsL copy num- ber. Third, despite the clear success of rpsL merodiploidy  for two strains tested in this work, this approach is not uni- versal, as study of S. ghanaensis rpsL derivatives showed.  The ribosome engineering appears to be especially success- ful for improvement of production of natural products of  polyketide or peptide types. As the latter is essential for  moenomycin production by S. ghanaensis (Makitrynskyy  et al. 2013), this may explain why rpsL merodiploids of S.  ghanaensis had unaltered antibiotic activity. Our work is one  more illustration of how little is known about chain of cause- to-consequence events that link rpsL mutations to changes in  secondary metabolism. These knowledge gaps notwithstand- ing, studies of rpsL and rpoB (Talà et al. 2009) merodiploidy  clearly demonstrate their practical merits.

There is growing appreciation of the idea that ribosomal  heterogeneity (caused by the presence of distinct rRNAs or  paralogous ribosomal proteins) has functional consequences  to the cell (Genuth and Barna 2018). Our (admittedly artifi- cial) case aligns well with this idea and is a unique model to  glean into the temporal dynamics of the ribosomal popula- tion of Streptomyces. For example, it has been shown for E.  coli that composition of ribosomes changes upon transition  to stationary phase (Lilleorg et al. 2018). The increase in the  fraction of  Strr clones in the late stage of submerged growth  of rpsLK88E merodiploid points to similar scenario. Namely,  once the mutant S12 protein is incorporated into majority  (or significant fraction) of cell’s ribosomes, it may lead to  phenotypic streptomycin resistance. The higher stability of  mutant  (Strr) ribosomes (Okamoto-Hosoya et al. 2003a) as  compared to wild type ones would also favor accumulation  of the former in the stationary phase. In our work rpsLK88E  was not the most efficient in terms of antibiotic overproduc- tion. If the latter is related to ability of  S12K88E to compete  with wild type S12 protein for incorporation into ribosome,  then “efficient” allele rpsLK88E+P91S might be expected to  confer earlier or higher streptomycin resistance to liquid  cultures. We believe that investigation of these issues will  provide new insights into the ribosome as a dynamic regu- latory device and ways to use rpsL mutations for practical  purposes. To conclude, genetically engineered rpsL merodiploids  possess unique features, making them distinct not only from  the wild type S. albus, but also from respective pure rpsL  mutants, described by us earlier. Given the relative technical  ease of merodiploid generation, it could be considered for  a wider application in studies of specialized metabolism of  Streptomyces.
